WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.260
So today I'm going to be talking about Shiny for Python without a server running Python.

00:00:14.260 --> 00:00:19.600
So Shiny for R has been around for 10 years now, it's kind of hard to believe.

00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:26.320
And if you want to deploy one of these applications, you have to have a server, oops, whoa, sorry

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:34.000
this clicker is a little sensitive, you have to have a server running R running Shiny.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.320
Yesterday Joe announced Shiny for Python.

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:43.160
And if you want to deploy one of these apps, you have to have a server running Python running

00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:45.759
Shiny.

00:00:45.759 --> 00:00:50.880
But there's another option where you can have a server that's running nothing.

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:56.759
Now before I go in-depth explaining what that means, I want to tell a story about the

00:00:56.759 --> 00:00:58.000
early days of Shiny.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:00.279
So this was back in 2013.

00:01:00.279 --> 00:01:03.279
Shiny had been around for about a year.

00:01:03.279 --> 00:01:08.199
And we had a server that was available where people could deploy their applications.

00:01:08.199 --> 00:01:12.279
And people were putting all sorts of interesting stuff there because there's, you know, scientists

00:01:12.279 --> 00:01:17.279
are using R and Shiny and they're doing all sorts of cool different things.

00:01:17.279 --> 00:01:23.480
One of the applications that showed up was a quiz by somebody who was a graduate student

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:27.360
in statistics at the time, named Josh Katz.

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:31.360
So long time users of Shiny know what this is about.

00:01:31.360 --> 00:01:35.519
This is one of the questions that he had on the quiz.

00:01:35.519 --> 00:01:39.559
So what do you call the insect that flies around in the summer and has a rear section

00:01:39.559 --> 00:01:42.239
that glows in the dark?

00:01:42.239 --> 00:01:45.400
You could answer this, lightning bug, firefly.

00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:48.040
I use them interchangeably or other.

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:55.239
So people would go to this, they'd select their answer, and it would display a map.

00:01:55.239 --> 00:01:59.080
So in the green areas here, this is where people tend to say firefly, the blue areas

00:01:59.080 --> 00:02:03.000
are where people tend to say lightning bug, and the red areas are where people use those

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:04.000
two words interchangeably.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:05.000
All right.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.559
Let's just do one more.

00:02:07.559 --> 00:02:08.559
For fun.

00:02:08.559 --> 00:02:10.559
If I can get it to go.

00:02:10.559 --> 00:02:11.559
Okay.

00:02:11.559 --> 00:02:14.919
How do you pronounce mayonnaise?

00:02:14.919 --> 00:02:24.360
So with three syllables, mayonnaise, with two syllables, mayonnaise, or I use both interchangeably.

00:02:24.360 --> 00:02:25.440
So here's the map.

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:30.919
In red is where people tend to say mayonnaise, and in blue is where people say mayonnaise,

00:02:30.919 --> 00:02:36.119
and the green is where people use them interchangeably, but there doesn't seem to be a lot on this

00:02:36.119 --> 00:02:37.119
map.

00:02:37.119 --> 00:02:38.479
All right.

00:02:38.479 --> 00:02:44.679
So you'd answer a lot of these questions, and at the end, it would generate a map for

00:02:44.679 --> 00:02:55.360
you showing how similar your personal dialect is to your regional dialects in the United

00:02:55.360 --> 00:02:56.360
States.

00:02:56.360 --> 00:03:02.000
Now, this isn't my map, but this is actually pretty close to me.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.119
The red is where your dialect is more similar to the regional dialect.

00:03:05.119 --> 00:03:10.440
So in this case, it's most similar to Northern California, and blue is where it's least similar.

00:03:10.440 --> 00:03:15.600
Now these maps were all generated dynamically, and that was a little bit computationally

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:21.320
expensive, but when you're dealing with, like, four or five people, that's not, you know,

00:03:21.320 --> 00:03:27.699
four or five simultaneous users, that's not a big deal, but this got out into some I believe

00:03:27.699 --> 00:03:32.800
it got out into some linguistics blog, and then it got picked up by the media.

00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:34.839
This is Business Insider.

00:03:34.839 --> 00:03:38.559
There was an article that ended up here, and my understanding actually was that this was

00:03:38.559 --> 00:03:42.399
the most popular article on their website that year.

00:03:42.399 --> 00:03:47.600
So it got picked up here and some other outlets, and it ended up driving a lot of traffic to

00:03:47.600 --> 00:03:49.240
our server.

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:53.720
So at some point, we had thousands of simultaneous users, and our server went down, and we had

00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:58.639
to spin up new servers in AWS to handle all that computational load.

00:03:58.639 --> 00:04:03.339
And this was back before we had these automated scaling and hosting systems that we have now.

00:04:03.339 --> 00:04:05.880
So that was a very manual process, ended up being very expensive.

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:08.619
We spent thousands of dollars running all these servers.

00:04:08.619 --> 00:04:09.619
But we survived.

00:04:09.619 --> 00:04:16.339
But you know, this raises an interesting question, which is, wouldn't it be nice if we didn't

00:04:16.339 --> 00:04:20.579
have to do all that computation on the server?

00:04:20.579 --> 00:04:23.500
So what are some ways of not doing the computation on the server?

00:04:23.500 --> 00:04:27.260
One thing you can do is maybe you can precompute the results.

00:04:27.260 --> 00:04:31.859
So sometimes you can do this.

00:04:31.859 --> 00:04:33.859
And sometimes you can't.

00:04:33.859 --> 00:04:36.299
Oh, sorry.

00:04:36.299 --> 00:04:37.779
Clicker problems here.

00:04:37.779 --> 00:04:38.779
Okay.

00:04:38.779 --> 00:04:39.779
Sometimes you can't.

00:04:39.779 --> 00:04:43.980
So some of those maps could have been pregenerated, and actually Josh changed his app to do that,

00:04:43.980 --> 00:04:47.500
but that final one with your personalized map could not be.

00:04:47.500 --> 00:04:48.500
All right.

00:04:48.500 --> 00:04:50.940
What about doing computation on the client?

00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:54.000
Well, you have a couple options here.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:58.339
So one is to do the computation in the web browser.

00:04:58.339 --> 00:05:03.760
But if you know something about web browsers, you know that the only language they understand

00:05:03.760 --> 00:05:06.760
is JavaScript.

00:05:06.760 --> 00:05:11.440
So therefore, you must write your application in JavaScript.

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:14.640
And that can be a problem if you're doing data science, because a lot of the tools that

00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:20.399
you're used to might not exist in JavaScript.

00:05:20.399 --> 00:05:22.519
So how about another option?

00:05:22.519 --> 00:05:26.679
Send the code and data to the client and let the user run the code on their computer.

00:05:26.679 --> 00:05:31.480
So in order to do this, though, you need to duplicate your computing environment on their

00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:32.480
computer.

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:36.640
And doing this, duplicating your computing environment is difficult, and it's a lot of

00:05:36.640 --> 00:05:37.640
work.

00:05:37.640 --> 00:05:42.320
And you can't reasonably expect somebody to take that survey, that fun survey, and have

00:05:42.320 --> 00:05:48.279
to install R or Python and a whole bunch of packages just to do that.

00:05:49.279 --> 00:05:56.320
Well, this is actually the story of how things were back then, but things have changed.

00:05:56.320 --> 00:06:02.000
So this part here about web browsers can only run JavaScript, that's actually no longer

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:03.600
true.

00:06:03.600 --> 00:06:08.880
And the corollary is also not true anymore.

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:12.320
So what other language do web browsers support now?

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:17.660
Well, there's something called WebAssembly, or it's sometimes abbreviated WASM.

00:06:17.660 --> 00:06:22.980
This is a binary format for programs that can run in web browsers.

00:06:22.980 --> 00:06:26.100
It's not a language that you'd write by hand normally.

00:06:26.100 --> 00:06:31.260
Usually you'd write code in C or C++ or some other languages and compile it to WebAssembly,

00:06:31.260 --> 00:06:35.899
and then you can run it in the browser at near-native speeds.

00:06:35.899 --> 00:06:42.700
So it turns out Python is written in C, and there's actually a port of Python called PyEdite

00:06:42.700 --> 00:06:46.380
which compiles to WebAssembly and can run in the web browser.

00:06:46.380 --> 00:06:50.820
And of course, I have to mention WebR, which is a project that George Stagg started and

00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:53.500
is working on, which is R compiled to WebAssembly.

00:06:53.500 --> 00:06:57.220
But this is still in the early stages, so I'm not going to talk more about it in this

00:06:57.220 --> 00:06:58.220
presentation.

00:06:58.220 --> 00:06:59.220
All right.

00:06:59.220 --> 00:07:03.380
So let's go back to doing computation on the client.

00:07:03.380 --> 00:07:10.100
So this option two here, this problem here, duplicating a computing environment is difficult.

00:07:10.100 --> 00:07:14.859
Well, actually, if you compile your computing environment to WebAssembly, you can send it

00:07:14.859 --> 00:07:20.179
to the web browser, and this actually becomes very easy to duplicate the computing environment.

00:07:20.179 --> 00:07:21.179
So we'll cross that out.

00:07:21.179 --> 00:07:24.260
And then we have this new combination of options one and two.

00:07:24.260 --> 00:07:29.540
So we send the code and data and the computing environment in WebAssembly to the client and

00:07:29.540 --> 00:07:32.619
then run all of that in the web browser.

00:07:32.619 --> 00:07:35.380
All right.

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:37.619
So we have done this with Shiny.

00:07:37.619 --> 00:07:44.700
So we've put together Shiny and Python and WebAssembly, and we put it together into something

00:07:44.700 --> 00:07:46.940
that we are calling Shiny Live.

00:07:46.940 --> 00:07:48.739
All right.

00:07:48.739 --> 00:07:51.940
So I'm not going to tell you a whole lot more about it right now.

00:07:51.940 --> 00:07:53.540
I'm just going to show you what you can do with it.

00:07:53.540 --> 00:07:58.859
So how many people here have gone to the documentation website for Shiny for Python?

00:07:58.859 --> 00:07:59.980
Okay.

00:07:59.980 --> 00:08:05.260
So if you did that, that's great, you might have seen something like this.

00:08:05.260 --> 00:08:12.700
So this is this web page here, and then there's a running application there.

00:08:12.700 --> 00:08:15.700
And I'll just show you that it's actually running.

00:08:15.700 --> 00:08:19.019
Well, this is just a video, but...

00:08:19.019 --> 00:08:23.779
So this is a histogram, you move a slider, and, you know, it regenerates some data and

00:08:23.779 --> 00:08:25.579
redraws the histogram.

00:08:25.579 --> 00:08:26.579
Okay.

00:08:26.579 --> 00:08:31.260
So what you might not have known is that you were already using Shiny Live.

00:08:31.260 --> 00:08:36.340
These applications on the website are not hosted on a server that's running Python.

00:08:36.340 --> 00:08:41.059
These examples are all running inside of the web browser.

00:08:41.059 --> 00:08:45.820
So you can go and you can make changes to this application.

00:08:45.820 --> 00:08:47.380
We'll do that up here.

00:08:47.380 --> 00:08:51.960
Let's just change this one so it generates a uniform distribution.

00:08:51.960 --> 00:08:55.659
So I'll take out some of the UI stuff, make some UI modifications.

00:08:55.659 --> 00:08:56.659
Don't worry about the details about this.

00:08:56.659 --> 00:09:00.179
You just have to know that I'm changing some code.

00:09:00.179 --> 00:09:06.099
And after we make those changes, then you can hit the play button, and you can see that

00:09:06.099 --> 00:09:08.200
now it's generating uniform distribution.

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:14.719
So again, all of that, the editor, and this application viewer panel, and Shiny itself,

00:09:14.719 --> 00:09:16.400
all of that is running inside the web browser.

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:17.919
There's no server running Python.

00:09:17.919 --> 00:09:18.919
All right.

00:09:18.919 --> 00:09:23.039
So what are some other fun things you can do with this?

00:09:23.039 --> 00:09:26.400
All right.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:32.280
If you start on the main web page, and then there's an examples button.

00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:35.320
You can click to browse some examples.

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:36.559
You don't have to be able to really read it.

00:09:36.640 --> 00:09:38.880
But on the sidebar, there's some interesting examples there.

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:42.880
One of them is a simulation of the moon orbiting the earth.

00:09:42.880 --> 00:09:43.880
All right.

00:09:43.880 --> 00:09:45.320
And I'm just going to...

00:09:45.320 --> 00:09:49.119
So what we have here is the code editor and then the running application over there.

00:09:49.119 --> 00:09:51.239
And again, this is all running inside the web browser.

00:09:51.239 --> 00:09:56.119
There's no server in the back running Python.

00:09:56.119 --> 00:09:59.559
So you can make changes to the initial speed of the earth.

00:09:59.559 --> 00:10:03.119
And then if you do that, you can see how the moon will follow it as it orbits.

00:10:03.119 --> 00:10:05.859
But let's say, you know, I want to make some changes to this.

00:10:05.859 --> 00:10:07.020
This app is a little complicated.

00:10:07.020 --> 00:10:08.739
I want to simplify a little bit.

00:10:08.739 --> 00:10:16.380
So let's go ahead and do that really fast.

00:10:16.380 --> 00:10:20.619
So you can make these changes right in the browser and rerun the application and try

00:10:20.619 --> 00:10:22.099
all sorts of new things out.

00:10:22.099 --> 00:10:23.099
All right.

00:10:23.099 --> 00:10:24.419
So here we are.

00:10:24.419 --> 00:10:26.020
We've simplified the application a little bit.

00:10:26.020 --> 00:10:29.020
I know it looks pretty similar, but it is actually simpler.

00:10:29.020 --> 00:10:33.179
And maybe we've learned a lot about using Shiny by doing this.

00:10:33.179 --> 00:10:36.460
Now, you might want to share this with people, right?

00:10:36.460 --> 00:10:44.099
Normally to do that, you would have to deploy it to some server that's running Shiny.

00:10:44.099 --> 00:10:47.059
But there's another option here with Shiny live.

00:10:47.059 --> 00:10:48.460
And I'm going to zoom in a little bit.

00:10:48.460 --> 00:10:51.619
I know this still may be hard to see, but I'll show it even closer later.

00:10:51.619 --> 00:10:53.260
So there's a share button.

00:10:53.260 --> 00:10:58.219
And then when you click on that, it will provide these two sharing links.

00:10:58.219 --> 00:10:59.219
And one of the...

00:10:59.219 --> 00:11:01.099
The top one says editor URL.

00:11:01.099 --> 00:11:07.099
And you can copy that URL, send it to somebody, and when they paste it in their web browser,

00:11:07.099 --> 00:11:11.619
they'll open it up and they will see the application running in their browser as well.

00:11:11.619 --> 00:11:15.640
And they have that editor panel and the running application.

00:11:15.640 --> 00:11:19.640
So this is good if the person you're sending it to is interested in the code and looking

00:11:19.640 --> 00:11:22.219
at it or modifying it.

00:11:22.219 --> 00:11:25.260
But maybe the person is not interested in that.

00:11:25.260 --> 00:11:27.940
Maybe they just want to see the application itself.

00:11:27.940 --> 00:11:30.619
So there's another link, application URL.

00:11:30.619 --> 00:11:34.780
You can copy that and send it to them.

00:11:34.780 --> 00:11:42.059
And then if they put that in their browser, it will open it up and it will be running

00:11:42.059 --> 00:11:45.539
that application in the full window.

00:11:45.539 --> 00:11:47.299
All right.

00:11:47.299 --> 00:11:52.460
So you might be wondering, like, hey, how much does this cost?

00:11:52.460 --> 00:11:54.219
How do I sign up for this?

00:11:54.219 --> 00:11:57.500
And the answer to those questions is it doesn't cost anything and you don't have to sign up

00:11:57.500 --> 00:11:59.640
for anything to use this.

00:11:59.659 --> 00:12:01.559
So we'll take a look at this URL.

00:12:01.559 --> 00:12:03.840
This might help explain things a little bit.

00:12:03.840 --> 00:12:05.559
So this is what the URL looks like.

00:12:05.559 --> 00:12:11.520
So it's shinylive.io.py editor and then code equals and then there's this big string.

00:12:11.520 --> 00:12:19.479
So that string is actually that whole application code encoded into the URL.

00:12:19.479 --> 00:12:24.760
And when you make a request, when you send that to somebody and they go visit that, the

00:12:24.760 --> 00:12:31.280
web browser makes a request just for this first part, the part in blue.

00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:35.799
So it requests Shiny Live, hey, send me all this Shiny Live stuff, the WebAssembly and

00:12:35.799 --> 00:12:38.320
JavaScript stuff.

00:12:38.320 --> 00:12:40.880
And Python stuff, of course.

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:42.900
It does not send this part to the server.

00:12:42.900 --> 00:12:44.799
That part is just in their browser.

00:12:44.799 --> 00:12:48.840
And so the browser then takes Shiny Live, decodes the application, and then runs it

00:12:48.840 --> 00:12:50.599
all inside the browser.

00:12:50.599 --> 00:12:55.359
So that means that the server is just serving these files without having to think about

00:12:55.359 --> 00:12:56.359
it.

00:12:56.359 --> 00:12:57.359
It just sends out tons of files.

00:12:57.359 --> 00:13:00.280
And that's really easy for web servers to do.

00:13:00.280 --> 00:13:08.159
Now, you might be thinking, well, sharing Shiny apps with a URL, that might be fun.

00:13:08.159 --> 00:13:12.719
But maybe the app and data is too big to make a reasonably sized URL.

00:13:12.719 --> 00:13:16.479
I mean, browsers can actually handle, from testing I found, really large URLs these days,

00:13:16.479 --> 00:13:18.000
like even in the megabytes.

00:13:18.599 --> 00:13:24.320
You don't typically want to send a huge URL like that.

00:13:24.320 --> 00:13:29.559
Maybe it feels weird to encode an app in a giant URL.

00:13:29.559 --> 00:13:32.559
That just seems strange.

00:13:32.559 --> 00:13:37.119
Or maybe, if I can get this clicker to work, maybe I don't want to depend on the server

00:13:37.119 --> 00:13:42.080
at Shinyapps.io, which I don't have any control over.

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:46.440
Well, I have control over it, but you don't.

00:13:46.440 --> 00:13:50.840
So another option is to deploy your Shiny live application.

00:13:50.840 --> 00:13:53.080
So in order to do this, there's two steps.

00:13:53.080 --> 00:13:59.400
The first is to save your Shiny live assets and application files to a directory and then

00:13:59.400 --> 00:14:05.400
upload that directory to a web hosting service like GitHub Pages or Netlify, Amazon S3, or

00:14:05.400 --> 00:14:06.400
CloudFlare Pages.

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:10.359
If you're old school, you can use an Apache web server.

00:14:10.359 --> 00:14:15.000
Or you can deploy to RStudio Connect, which is useful because it provides authentication

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:19.640
and access control if you don't want the whole world to be able to see the application.

00:14:19.640 --> 00:14:21.280
And let me show you how this works.

00:14:21.280 --> 00:14:23.679
So it's pretty simple.

00:14:23.679 --> 00:14:32.960
All right, so let's say I have my application files in a directory called myapp.

00:14:32.960 --> 00:14:37.000
Then there's a command line tool that comes with Shiny for Python called Shiny.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:40.960
And you say Shiny static myapp site.

00:14:40.960 --> 00:14:44.179
So site is the directory that we're writing it to.

00:14:44.359 --> 00:14:47.820
And it downloads and copies the Shiny live assets and puts them in there.

00:14:47.820 --> 00:14:52.840
And then it also copies the application files and puts them in there.

00:14:52.840 --> 00:14:56.780
And so now we have a directory, we'll take a look here, a directory called site.

00:14:56.780 --> 00:15:03.659
And then we can test, hey, can I actually serve this site directory and have people

00:15:03.659 --> 00:15:06.859
run my application?

00:15:06.859 --> 00:15:12.140
So we'll just run the simple web server, Python web server, and look at visit localhost.

00:15:12.140 --> 00:15:15.059
And then it will load the application right here.

00:15:15.059 --> 00:15:19.580
All right, now at this point, this is when you can take that set of files and just upload

00:15:19.580 --> 00:15:25.340
it to your static web hosting service, whatever that may be.

00:15:25.340 --> 00:15:27.960
Let's take a look at the deployment model here.

00:15:27.960 --> 00:15:31.059
So for traditional Shiny app deployment, you have a server that's running R or running

00:15:31.059 --> 00:15:32.380
Python.

00:15:32.380 --> 00:15:33.840
And computers connect to it.

00:15:33.840 --> 00:15:37.099
And when they connect to it, they maintain this open connection.

00:15:37.099 --> 00:15:38.820
The user interacts with it a little bit.

00:15:38.820 --> 00:15:39.820
It sends data to the server.

00:15:39.820 --> 00:15:44.460
The server does some computation, and it sends some information back.

00:15:44.460 --> 00:15:49.599
For Shiny live app deployment, you have a server that doesn't run R or Python.

00:15:49.599 --> 00:16:00.140
When the user connects to it, it sends Python and the app code and Shiny, of course, to

00:16:00.140 --> 00:16:01.219
those computers.

00:16:01.219 --> 00:16:04.320
And all of that stuff runs inside of those client computers.

00:16:04.320 --> 00:16:07.539
And it's very easy for a server to just send those files.

00:16:07.539 --> 00:16:10.299
That's not a computationally intensive thing to do.

00:16:10.299 --> 00:16:13.299
So you can serve a lot of users this way.

00:16:13.299 --> 00:16:14.299
Okay.

00:16:14.299 --> 00:16:18.260
Let's talk about the benefits of Shiny live, to summarize.

00:16:18.260 --> 00:16:21.619
So the entire application runs on the client instead of the server, so there's no computational

00:16:21.619 --> 00:16:24.099
load on the server.

00:16:24.099 --> 00:16:27.500
It's really easy to share these applications.

00:16:27.500 --> 00:16:30.679
It's easy to deploy them to a static web hosting service.

00:16:30.679 --> 00:16:35.940
And it's easy to scale them, because that's what these static web hosting services do.

00:16:35.940 --> 00:16:40.219
That's their bread and butter, and it's very cheap.

00:16:40.219 --> 00:16:45.780
And it works on devices without Python installed, so like Chromebooks or iPads or phones.

00:16:45.780 --> 00:16:50.739
And this is not just for viewing the application, but you can even edit the applications and

00:16:50.739 --> 00:16:53.820
play with them on there.

00:16:53.820 --> 00:16:57.619
So it's not all sunshine and rainbows.

00:16:57.619 --> 00:17:00.239
There's also a few drawbacks and limitations.

00:17:00.239 --> 00:17:04.339
So one is that not all packages are available on Pyedide.

00:17:04.339 --> 00:17:08.979
So Pyedide contains a lot of packages in the Python scientific stack, including pandas

00:17:08.979 --> 00:17:12.979
and matplotlib, but not all packages for Python.

00:17:12.979 --> 00:17:17.459
You can install packages from PyPI if they're written in pure Python and don't have any

00:17:17.459 --> 00:17:18.979
compiled code.

00:17:18.979 --> 00:17:24.699
So hopefully this situation will improve in the future, but that's what it is right now.

00:17:24.699 --> 00:17:29.959
The code and data for the application is sent to the web browser, so there's no secrets.

00:17:29.959 --> 00:17:33.579
Somebody can, in principle, look at all the code and data for your application, if they

00:17:33.579 --> 00:17:35.939
can see your app.

00:17:35.939 --> 00:17:39.260
It's not good for large amounts of data, like if you've got 100 megabytes of data that your

00:17:39.260 --> 00:17:43.900
application is operating on, you probably don't want to send that to somebody's web

00:17:43.900 --> 00:17:44.900
browser.

00:17:44.900 --> 00:17:45.900
That's a lot.

00:17:45.900 --> 00:17:49.380
It's not unheard of, but that is a lot.

00:17:49.380 --> 00:17:54.619
So the download size, for a basic application, the browser will download about 13 megabytes

00:17:54.619 --> 00:18:02.219
of stuff, and if you're loading packages from there, like pandas, it's just going to go

00:18:02.219 --> 00:18:06.020
up from there.

00:18:06.020 --> 00:18:09.180
But fortunately, browser caching will speed up subsequent visits.

00:18:09.180 --> 00:18:12.380
So the first time somebody views it, it might be slow, and especially in this conference

00:18:12.380 --> 00:18:15.739
Wi-Fi, the first time you visit one of these may be a little bit slow, but then in later

00:18:15.739 --> 00:18:19.540
visits it should be really, really fast.

00:18:19.540 --> 00:18:24.739
And finally, the browser security sandbox restricts network connectivity.

00:18:24.739 --> 00:18:28.180
But the good news is, if Shiny live doesn't work for your application, you always have

00:18:28.180 --> 00:18:31.140
the option to do a traditional Shiny app deployment.

00:18:31.140 --> 00:18:35.140
You can learn this one framework, Shiny, and when it's appropriate, deploy it with

00:18:35.140 --> 00:18:40.900
Shiny live, and if that doesn't work for you, you can deploy it with a traditional deployment,

00:18:40.900 --> 00:18:43.420
just by learning one framework.

00:18:43.420 --> 00:18:48.699
So this is where you can learn more about it, shiny.rstudio.com.py.

00:18:48.699 --> 00:18:51.900
There's a link at the top for Shiny live.

00:18:51.900 --> 00:18:55.260
So also, it's still experimental.

00:18:55.260 --> 00:18:56.500
Please keep that in mind.

00:18:56.500 --> 00:19:00.660
We're still learning a lot about it, and, you know, so we can't wait to see what you're

00:19:00.660 --> 00:19:06.020
going to do with it, because we want to learn what kinds of possibilities people, what the

00:19:06.020 --> 00:19:09.979
possibilities are, and hopefully you'll be able to teach us that.

00:19:09.979 --> 00:19:14.819
And of course, I know everyone is thinking about this, yes, we're hoping to do this with

00:19:14.819 --> 00:19:18.699
Shiny for R, but there's a lot of work that needs to be done before we can get started

00:19:18.699 --> 00:19:19.699
on this.

00:19:19.699 --> 00:19:20.699
Thank you.

00:19:20.739 --> 00:19:21.739
Thank you.

00:19:21.739 --> 00:19:22.739
Thank you.

00:19:22.739 --> 00:19:23.739
Thank you.

